 Act. Justice Samuel Chase of the Supreme Court presided at Callender's trial. Callender's counsel attempted to argue the unconstitutionality of the Sedition law, but Chase refused to permit the jury to determine the constitutionality of a federal statute. Callender was convicted, and Chase fined him $200 and sentenced him to nine months in jail. Jefferson pardoned Callender when he became President, as he did the others convicted under the Sedition Act, and also gave him fifty dollars towards his fine, the last in a series of payments he made to support the journalist. Callender however, enraged by what he perceived as a slight by the new President, wrote a series of attacks on Jefferson similar to those earlier launched against Adams, and which included the assertion that Jefferson had fathered children by a slave woman.&lt;ref&gt;Miller, John C. ''Crisis in Freedom: The Alien and Sedition Acts'' (New York: Little Brown and Company 1951) pp. 211-220.&lt;/ref&gt;

===A member of Congress===
[[Matthew Lyon]], born in Ireland, was a Democratic-Republican congressman from Vermont. He was indicted under the Sedition Act for an essay he had written in the ''Vermont Journal'' accusing the administration of &quot;ridiculous pomp, foolish adulation, and selfish avarice&quot;. While awaiting trial, Lyon commenced publication of ''Lyon's Republican Magazine'', subtitled &quot;The Scourge of Aristocracy&quot;. Supreme Court justice Paterson presiding at trial, denied Lyon's defense of unconstitutionality of the statute, fined Lyon $1,000 and sentenced him to four months in prison.  While in prison, Lyon continued to write, and also won re-election. After his release, he returned to Congress.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|author=Foner, Eric|title=Give Me Liberty!|pages=282–283|year=2008|publisher=W.W. Norton and Company|isbn=978-0-393-93257-7}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;Miller, John C. ''Crisis in Freedom: The Alien and Sedition Acts'' (New York: Little Brown and Company 1951) pp. 102-108.&lt;/ref&gt;

===Private individuals===
Luther Baldwin, a private citizen, was indicted for a comment he made during a visit by President Adams to Newark, New Jersey. The President was greeted by a crowd and by a committee that saluted him by firing a cannon. A bystander said, &quot;There goes the President and they are firing at his ass.&quot; Baldwin replied that he did not care &quot;if they fired through his ass.&quot; He was convicted in the federal court for speaking &quot;seditious words tending to defame the President and Government of the United States&quot; and fined $100.&lt;ref&gt;{{citation|author=Smith, J.|title=Freedom's Fetters|pages=270–274|year=1956}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;Miller, John C. ''Crisis in Freedom: The Alien and Sedition Acts'' (New York: Little Brown and Company 1951) pp. 112-114.&lt;/ref&gt;

In November 1798, [[David Brown (Massachusetts)|David Brown]] led a group in Dedham, Massachusetts in setting up a [[liberty pole]] with the words, &quot;No Stamp Act, No Sedition Act, No Alien Bills, No Land Tax, downfall to the Tyrants of America; peace and retirement to the President; Long Live the Vice President&quot;.&lt;ref name = Perilous&gt;{{cite book | url = http://books.google.com/books?id=S7ScI3Ia25sC&amp;pg=PA64 | page = 64 | title = Perilous times: free speech in wartime from the Sedition Act of 1798 to the war on terrorism | first = Geoffrey R. | last = Stone | publisher = W. W. Norton &amp; Company | year = 2004 | ISBN = 0393058808, ISBN 978-0-393-05880-2 }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book | url = http://books.google.com/books?id=T1F1H2KUj80C&amp;pg=PA420#v=onepage&amp;q=&amp;f=false | page = 420 | title = The American counterrevolution: a retreat from liberty, 1783-1800 | first = Larry E. | last = Tise | publisher = Stackpole Books | year = 1998 | ISBN = 081170100X, ISBN 978-0-8117-0100-6 }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book | url = http://books.google.com/books?id=_VOeQqUhTAsC&amp;pg=PA88 | page = 88 | title = Free speech, &quot;the people's darling privilege&quot;: struggles for freedom of expression in American history | first = Michael Kent | last = Curtis | publisher = Duke University Press | year = 2000 | ISBN = 0822325292, ISBN 978-0-8223-2529-1 }}&lt;/ref&gt; Brown was arrested in Andover, Massachusetts, but because he could not afford the $4,000 bail, he was taken to Salem for trial.&lt;ref name = American&gt;{{cite book | url = http://books.google.com/books?id=T1F1H2KUj80C&amp;pg=PA421 | page = 421 | title = The American counterrevolution: a retreat from liberty, 1783-1800 | first = Larry E. | last = Tise | publisher = Stackpole Books | year = 1998 | ISBN = 081170100X, ISBN 978-0-8117-0100-6 }}&lt;/ref&gt;  Brown was tried in June 1799.&lt;ref name = Perilous/&gt;  Brown  pled guilty but Justice Samuel Chase asked him to name others who had assisted him.&lt;ref name = Perilous/&gt;  Brown refused, was fined $480,&lt;ref name = American/&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book | url = http://books.google.com/books?id=hfiPFq5PEH8C&amp;pg=RA1-PA55 | page = 55 | title = What Kind of Nation: Thomas Jefferson, John Marshall, and the Epic Struggle to Create a United States | first = James F. | last = Simon | publisher = Simon and Schuster | year = 2003 | ISBN = 0684848716, ISBN 978-0-684-84871-6 }}&lt;/ref&gt; and sentenced to eighteen months in prison, the most severe sentence ever imposed under the Sedition Act.&lt;ref name = Perilous/&gt;&lt;ref name = American/&gt;

===Political nature of the prosecutions===

The Republican prediction that the Sedition Act would be used as a tool to assure the primacy of the Federalists was confirmed by the fact that no Federalist editor was indicted for equally rough language towards Republicans. John C. Miller writes that &quot;the Sedition Act was not construed to mean that the Federalists were to cease maligning and whipping Jefferson&quot;, who was, among numerous other assertions, called a 'vain author, false prophet, and thorough-bred Frenchman&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;Miller, John C. ''Crisis in Freedom: The Alien and Sedition Acts'' (New York: Little Brown and Company 1951) p. 131-132.&lt;/ref&gt;

===Consequences of the Alien Act===

While government authorities prepared lists of aliens for deportation, many aliens fled the country during the debate over the Alien and Sedition Acts, and Adams never signed a deportation order.&lt;ref&gt;Miller, John C. ''Crisis in Freedom: The Alien and Sedition Acts'' (New York: Little Brown and Company 1951) p. 187-193.&lt;/ref&gt;

==Aftermath==

The Republicans used the Alien and Sedition Acts as one of their principal issues in the [[United States presidential election, 1800|1800 election]], in which Federalists at all levels, were turned out of power. Thomas Jefferson, upon assuming the Presidency, pardoned all of those still serving sentences under the Sedition Act.&lt;ref&gt;Miller, John C. Crisis in Freedom: The Alien and Sedition Acts (New York: Little Brown and Company 1951) p. 231.&lt;/ref&gt;  

In 1832, the House [[Judiciary Committee]] denounced the Sedition Act as unconstitutional, permitting the refund of fines which had been paid under it.&lt;ref&gt;Mott, Frank L., ''Jefferson and the Press'' (Baton Rouge: Louisiana State University Press 1943), p. 37.&lt;/ref&gt;

The Alien Enemies Act remained in force and was used as a basis for the [[Japanese American internment|internment of Japanese citizens]] during World War II. 

While the Sedition Act was never reviewed by the Supreme Court, subsequent mentions in Supreme Court opinions have assumed that it was unconstitutional. In the seminal free speech case of ''[[New York Times Co. v. Sullivan]]'', the Court declared, &quot;Although the Sedition Act was never tested in this Court, the attack upon its validity has carried the day in the court of history.&quot; 376 U.S. 254, 276 (1964). In a [[concurring opinion]] in ''Watts v. United States'', which involved an alleged threat against President [[Lyndon Johnson]], [[William O. Douglas]] noted, &quot;The Alien and Sedition Laws constituted one of our sorriest chapters; and I had thought we had done with them forever ... Suppression of speech as an effective police measure is an old, old device, outlawed by our Constitution.&quot;&lt;ref&gt;{{citation|title=Watts v. United States, 394 U.S. 705|url=http://caselaw.lp.findlaw.com/scripts/getcase.pl?court=us&amp;vol=394&amp;invol=705}}&lt;/ref&gt;

