  <page>
    <title>Acephali</title>
    <id>3266</id>
    <revision>
      <id>422795899</id>
      <timestamp>2011-04-07T02:35:23Z</timestamp>
      <contributor>
        <username>Amirobot</username>
        <id>7390477</id>
      </contributor>
      <minor />
      <comment>r2.7.1) (robot Adding: [[ar:انعدام الرأس]]</comment>
      <text xml:space="preserve">{{confusing|date=April 2010}}
{{wiktionary}}
'''Acephali''' (from the [[Greek language]] ''a-'', &quot;without,&quot; and ''kephalos'', &quot;head&quot;) is a term applied to several sects as having no head or leader.&lt;ref name=&quot;brewer&quot;&gt;{{cite book | last = Brewer | first = E. Cobham | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = The Dictionary of Phrase and Fable | publisher = Avenel Books | date = 1978 (reprint of 1894 version) | location = Edwinstowe, England | pages = 9 | isbn = 0-517-25921-4}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In particular, the term refers to a strict [[monophysite]] sect that separated itself, in the end of the 5th century, from the rule of [[Peter III of Alexandria|Peter Mongus]], [[List of Patriarchs of Alexandria|Patriarch of Alexandria]], and remained &quot;without king or bishop&quot; until they were reconciled by [[Pope Mark II of Alexandria|Mark II]] (799 - 819).

The term is also used to denote ''clerici vagantes'', i.e. clergy without title or benefice, picking up a living anyhow. Certain persons in [[England]] during the reign of King [[Henry I of England]] were called Acephali because they had no lands by virtue of which they could acknowledge a superior lord.&lt;ref name=&quot;brewer&quot;/&gt;

The name is also given to certain legendary races described by ancient naturalists and 
geographers as having no heads, their mouths and eyes being in their breasts, generally identified with [[Pliny the Elder|Pliny's]] [[Blemmyes (legendary creatures)|Blemmyae]].&lt;ref name=&quot;brewer&quot;/&gt; They live in [[Libya]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book|title=The Element Encyclopedia of Magical Creatures|publisher=Harper Collins|isbn=0-00-720873-1|year=2005|last=Matthews|first=John &amp; Caitlin|page=6}}&lt;/ref&gt;

