  <page>
    <title>Antioxidant</title>
    <id>3277</id>
    <revision>
      <id>429664860</id>
      <timestamp>2011-05-18T03:08:29Z</timestamp>
      <contributor>
        <username>Materialscientist</username>
        <id>7852030</id>
      </contributor>
      <minor />
      <comment>[[Help:Reverting|Reverted]] edits by [[Special:Contributions/204.195.33.190|204.195.33.190]] ([[User talk:204.195.33.190|talk]]) to last version by Materialscientist</comment>
      <text xml:space="preserve">{{pp-move-indef}}
{{Multiple issues
| long = April 2011
| weasel = March 2011
}}
[[Image:Glutathione-3D-vdW.png|thumb|right|300px|Space-filling model of the antioxidant [[metabolomics|metabolite]] [[glutathione]]. The yellow sphere is the [[redox|redox-active]] sulfur atom that provides antioxidant activity, while the red, blue, white, and dark grey spheres represent oxygen, nitrogen, hydrogen, and carbon atoms, respectively.]]

An '''antioxidant''' is a [[molecule]] capable of inhibiting the [[Redox|oxidation]] of other molecules. Oxidation is a [[chemical reaction]] that transfers [[electron]]s from a substance to an [[oxidizing agent]]. Oxidation reactions can produce [[Radical (chemistry)|free radical]]s.  In turn, these radicals can start [[chain reaction]]s.  When the chain reaction occurs in a [[cell (biology)|cell]], it can cause damage or death. When the chain reaction occurs in a purified monomer, it produces a polymer resin, such as a [[Thermoplastic|plastic]], a [[synthetic fiber]], or an [[Drying oil|oil paint film]].  Antioxidants terminate these chain reactions by removing free radical intermediates, and inhibit other oxidation reactions. They do this by being oxidized themselves, so antioxidants are often [[reducing agent]]s such as [[thiol]]s, [[ascorbic acid]] or [[polyphenol antioxidant|polyphenol]]s.&lt;ref name=&quot;Sies&quot; /&gt;

Although oxidation reactions are crucial for life, they can also be damaging; hence, [[plant]]s and [[animal]]s maintain complex systems of multiple types of antioxidants, such as [[glutathione]], [[vitamin C]], and [[vitamin E]] as well as [[enzyme]]s such as [[catalase]], [[superoxide dismutase]] and various [[peroxidase]]s. Low levels of antioxidants, or [[enzyme inhibitor|inhibition]] of the antioxidant enzymes, cause [[oxidative stress]] and may damage or kill cells.{{Citation needed|date=March 2011}}

As oxidative stress appears to be an important part of many human diseases, the use of antioxidants in [[pharmacology]] is intensively studied, particularly as treatments for [[stroke]] and [[neurodegenerative disease]]s. However, it is unknown whether oxidative stress is the cause or the consequence of disease.

Antioxidants are widely used as ingredients in [[dietary supplements]] and have been investigated for the prevention of diseases such as [[cancer]], [[coronary heart disease]] and even [[altitude sickness]]. Although initial studies suggested that antioxidant supplements might promote health, later large [[clinical trial]]s did not detect any benefit and suggested instead that excess supplementation is harmful.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |pages=341–8 |doi=10.1093/qjmed/hcp026 |title=Oral antioxidant supplementation does not prevent acute mountain sickness: double blind, randomized placebo-controlled trial |year=2009 |last1=Baillie |first1=J.K. |last2=Thompson |first2=A.A.R. |last3=Irving |first3=J.B. |last4=Bates |first4=M.G.D. |last5=Sutherland |first5=A.I. |last6=MacNee |first6=W. |last7=Maxwell |first7=S.R.J. |last8=Webb |first8=D.J. |journal=QJM |volume=102 |issue=5 |pmid=19273551}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |author=Bjelakovic G |title=Mortality in randomized trials of antioxidant supplements for primary and secondary prevention: systematic review and meta-analysis |journal=JAMA |volume=297 |issue=8 |pages=842–57 |year=2007 |pmid=17327526 |doi=10.1001/jama.297.8.842 |last2=Nikolova |first2=D |last3=Gluud |first3=LL |last4=Simonetti |first4=RG |last5=Gluud |first5=C}}&lt;/ref&gt; In addition to these uses of natural antioxidants in medicine, these compounds have many industrial uses, such as [[preservatives]] in food and cosmetics and preventing the degradation of [[rubber]] and [[gasoline]].

== History ==
As part of their adaptation from marine life, terrestrial plants began producing non-marine antioxidants such as [[ascorbic acid]] ([[Vitamin C]]), [[polyphenol antioxidant|polyphenol]]s and [[tocopherol]]s.  Further development of [[angiosperm]] plants between 50 and 200 million years ago, particularly during the [[Jurassic]] period, produced many antioxidant pigments evolved during the late [[Jurassic]] period as chemical defences against [[reactive oxygen species]] produced during [[photosynthesis]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |pages=113–26 |doi=10.1016/S1095-6433(02)00368-9 |title=Evolution of dietary antioxidants |year=2003 |last1=Benzie |first1=I |journal=Comparative Biochemistry and Physiology |volume=136 |pmid=14527634 |issue=1}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |pages=727–9 |doi=10.1089/10507250050137851 |title=Environmental Iodine Deficiency: A Challenge to the Evolution of Terrestrial Life? |year=2000 |last1=Venturi |first1=Sebastiano |last2=Donati |first2=Francesco M. |last3=Venturi |first3=Alessandro |last4=Venturi |first4=Mattia |journal=Thyroid |volume=10 |issue=8 |pmid=11014322}}&lt;/ref&gt; The term antioxidant originally was used to refer specifically to a chemical that prevented the consumption of oxygen. In the late 19th and early 20th centuries, extensive study was devoted to the uses of antioxidants in important industrial processes, such as the prevention of metal [[corrosion]], the [[vulcanization]] of rubber, and the [[polymerization]] of fuels in the [[fouling]] of [[internal combustion engine]]s.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |pages=177–92 |doi=10.1146/annurev.bi.16.070147.001141 |title=Antioxidants |year=1947 |last1=Mattill |first1=H A |journal=Annual Review of Biochemistry |volume=16 |pmid=20259061}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Early research on the role of antioxidants in biology focused on their use in preventing the oxidation of [[unsaturated fat]]s, which is the cause of [[rancidity]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |pmid=10335367 |year=1999 |last1=German |first1=JB |title=Food processing and lipid oxidation |volume=459 |pages=23–50 |journal=Advances in experimental medicine and biology}}&lt;/ref&gt; Antioxidant activity could be measured simply by placing the fat in a closed container with oxygen and measuring the rate of oxygen consumption. However, it was the identification of [[Vitamin A|vitamins A]], [[Vitamin C|C]], and [[Vitamin E|E]] as antioxidants that revolutionized the field and led to the realization of the importance of antioxidants in the biochemistry of [[Organism|living organisms]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |pmid=8821966 |year=1996 |last1=Jacob |first1=RA |title=Three eras of vitamin C discovery |volume=25 |pages=1–16 |journal=Sub-cellular biochemistry}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |pmid=9846200 |year=1998 |last1=Knight |first1=JA |title=Free radicals: Their history and current status in aging and disease |volume=28 |issue=6 |pages=331–46 |journal=Annals of clinical and laboratory science}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The possible [[mechanisms of action]] of antioxidants were first explored when it was recognized that a substance with anti-oxidative activity is likely to be one that is itself readily oxidized.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |last1=Moreau |last2=Dufraisse |year=1922 |journal=Comptes Rendus des Séances et Mémoires de la Société de Biologie |volume=86 |pages=321}}{{vs|missing article title, does oclc 20845936 have the correct journal title?|date=April 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt; Research into how [[vitamin E]] prevents the process of [[lipid peroxidation]] led to the identification of antioxidants as reducing agents that prevent oxidative reactions, often by [[scavenger (chemistry)|scavenging]] [[reactive oxygen species]] before they can damage cells.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |last1=Wolf |first1=George |pmid=15735064 |url=http://jn.nutrition.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&amp;pmid=15735064 |year=2005 |title=The discovery of the antioxidant function of vitamin E: The contribution of Henry A. Mattill |volume=135 |issue=3 |pages=363–6 |journal=The Journal of nutrition}}&lt;/ref&gt;

== The oxidative challenge in biology ==
{{Further|[[Oxidative stress]]}}

[[Image:L-ascorbic-acid-3D-balls.png|thumb|right|The structure of the antioxidant [[vitamin]] [[ascorbic acid]] (vitamin C).]]

A [[paradox]] in [[metabolism]] is that while the vast majority of complex [[life on Earth]] requires [[oxygen]] for its existence, oxygen is a highly reactive molecule that damages living organisms by producing [[reactive oxygen species]].&lt;ref name=&quot;Davies&quot;&gt;{{cite journal |pmid=8660387 |year=1995 |last1=Davies |first1=KJ |title=Oxidative stress: The paradox of aerobic life |volume=61 |pages=1–31 |journal=Biochemical Society symposium}}&lt;/ref&gt; Consequently, organisms contain a complex network of antioxidant [[metabolite]]s and [[enzyme]]s that work together to prevent oxidative damage to cellular components such as [[DNA]], [[protein]]s and [[lipid]]s.&lt;ref name=&quot;Sies&quot;&gt;{{cite journal |last1=Sies |first1=Helmut |pmid=9129943 |url=http://ep.physoc.org/cgi/pmidlookup?view=long&amp;pmid=9129943 |year=1997 |title=Oxidative stress: Oxidants and antioxidants |volume=82 |issue=2 |pages=291–5 |journal=Experimental physiology}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;Vertuani&quot;&gt;{{cite journal |pages=1677–94 |doi=10.2174/1381612043384655 |title=The Antioxidants and Pro-Antioxidants Network: An Overview |year=2004 |last1=Vertuani |first1=Silvia |last2=Angusti |first2=Angela |last3=Manfredini |first3=Stefano |journal=Current Pharmaceutical Design |volume=10 |issue=14 |pmid=15134565}}&lt;/ref&gt; In general, antioxidant systems either prevent these reactive species from being formed, or remove them before they can damage vital components of the cell.&lt;ref name=&quot;Sies&quot; /&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;Davies&quot; /&gt; However, since reactive oxygen species do have useful functions in cells, such as [[redox signaling]], the function of antioxidant systems is not to remove oxidants entirely, but instead to keep them at an optimum level.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |pages=1882–3 |doi=10.1126/science.1130481 |title=CELL SIGNALING: H2O2, a Necessary Evil for Cell Signaling |year=2006 |last1=Rhee |first1=S. G. |journal=Science |volume=312 |issue=5782 |pmid=16809515}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The reactive oxygen species produced in cells include [[hydrogen peroxide]] (H&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;O&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;), [[hypochlorous acid]] (HOCl), and [[free radicals]] such as the [[hydroxyl radical]] (·OH) and the [[superoxide|superoxide anion]] (O&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;sup&gt;−&lt;/sup&gt;).&lt;ref name=&quot;emfafb&quot;&gt;{{cite journal |pages=44–84 |doi=10.1016/j.biocel.2006.07.001 |title=Free radicals and antioxidants in normal physiological functions and human disease |year=2007 |last1=Valko |first1=M |last2=Leibfritz |first2=D |last3=Moncol |first3=J |last4=Cronin |first4=M |last5=Mazur |first5=M |last6=Telser |first6=J |journal=The International Journal of Biochemistry &amp; Cell Biology |volume=39}}&lt;/ref&gt; The hydroxyl radical is particularly unstable and will react rapidly and non-specifically with most biological molecules. This species is produced from hydrogen peroxide in [[catalysis|metal-catalyzed]] redox reactions such as the [[Fenton reaction]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |pages=321–36 |doi=10.1016/0891-5849(94)00159-H |title=Oxidative mechanisms in the toxicity of metal ions |year=1995 |last1=Stohs |first1=S |journal=Free Radical Biology and Medicine |volume=18 |issue=2 |pmid=7744317 |last2=Bagchi |first2=D}}&lt;/ref&gt; These oxidants can damage cells by starting chemical chain reactions such as lipid peroxidation, or by oxidizing DNA or proteins.&lt;ref name=&quot;Sies&quot; /&gt; Damage to DNA can cause [[mutation]]s and possibly [[cancer]], if not reversed by [[DNA repair]] mechanisms,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |pages=373–9 |doi=10.1515/BC.2006.050 |title=Mutagenesis and carcinogenesis caused by the oxidation of nucleic acids |year=2006 |last1=Nakabeppu |first1=Yusaku |last2=Sakumi |first2=Kunihiko |last3=Sakamoto |first3=Katsumi |last4=Tsuchimoto |first4=Daisuke |last5=Tsuzuki |first5=Teruhisa |last6=Nakatsu |first6=Yoshimichi |journal=Biological Chemistry |volume=387 |issue=4 |pmid=16606334}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |pages=37–56 |doi=10.1023/B:MCBI.0000049134.69131.89 |title=Role of oxygen radicals in DNA damage and cancer incidence |year=2004 |last1=Valko |first1=Marian |last2=Izakovic |first2=Mario |last3=Mazur |first3=Milan |last4=Rhodes |first4=Christopher J. |last5=Telser |first5=Joshua |journal=Molecular and Cellular Biochemistry |volume=266 |pmid=15646026 |issue=1–2}}&lt;/ref&gt; while damage to [[protein]]s causes enzyme inhibition, [[denaturation (biochemistry)|denaturation]] and [[proteasome|protein degradation]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |pages=1220–4 |doi=10.1126/science.1355616 |title=Protein oxidation and aging |year=1992 |last1=Stadtman |first1=E. |journal=Science |volume=257 |issue=5074 |pmid=1355616}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The use of oxygen as part of the process for generating metabolic energy produces reactive oxygen species.&lt;ref name=&quot;Raha&quot;&gt;{{cite journal |pages=502–8 |doi=10.1016/S0968-0004(00)01674-1 |title=Mitochondria, oxygen free radicals, disease and ageing |year=2000 |last1=Raha |first1=S |journal=Trends in Biochemical Sciences |volume=25 |issue=10 |pmid=11050436 |last2=Robinson |first2=BH}}&lt;/ref&gt; In this process, the superoxide anion is produced as a [[by-product]] of several steps in the [[electron transport chain]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |pages=159–64 |doi=10.1080/15216540152845957 |title=The Mitochondrial Production of Reactive Oxygen Species: Mechanisms and Implications in Human Pathology |year=2001 |last1=Lenaz |first1=Giorgio |journal=IUBMB Life |volume=52 |issue=3–5 |pmid=11798028}}&lt;/ref&gt; Particularly important is the reduction of [[coenzyme Q]] in [[complex III]], since a highly reactive free radical is formed as an intermediate (Q'''·'''&lt;sup&gt;−&lt;/sup&gt;). This unstable intermediate can lead to electron &quot;leakage&quot;, when electrons jump directly to oxygen and form the superoxide anion, instead of moving through the normal series of well-controlled reactions of the electron transport chain.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |pages=239–47 |doi=10.1038/35041687 |year=2000 |last1=Finkel |first1=Toren |last2=Holbrook |first2=Nikki J. |journal=Nature |volume=408 |issue=6809 |pmid=11089981 |title=Oxidants, oxidative stress and the biology of ageing}}&lt;/ref&gt; Peroxide is also produced from the oxidation of reduced [[flavoprotein]]s, such as [[complex I]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |pages=976–80 |doi=10.1042/BST0360976 |title=The production of reactive oxygen species by complex I |year=2008 |last1=Hirst |first1=Judy |last2=King |first2=Martin S. |last3=Pryde |first3=Kenneth R. |journal=Biochemical Society Transactions |volume=36 |issue=5}}&lt;/ref&gt; However, although these enzymes can produce oxidants, the relative importance of the electron transfer chain to other processes that generate peroxide is unclear.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |pages=48742–50 |doi=10.1074/jbc.M408754200 |title=Are Respiratory Enzymes the Primary Sources of Intracellular Hydrogen Peroxide? |year=2004 |last1=Seaver |first1=L. C. |journal=Journal of Biological Chemistry |volume=279 |issue=47 |pmid=15361522 |last2=Imlay |first2=JA}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;Pathways Ofoxidativedamage&quot;&gt;{{cite journal |pages=395–418 |doi=10.1146/annurev.micro.57.030502.090938 |title=Pathways Ofoxidativedamage |year=2003 |last1=Imlay |first1=James A. |journal=Annual Review of Microbiology |volume=57 |pmid=14527285}}&lt;/ref&gt; In [[plant]]s, [[algae]],  and [[cyanobacteria]], reactive oxygen species are also produced during [[photosynthesis]],&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |pages=2149–53 |doi=10.1126/science.1078002 |title=Antioxidants in Photosynthesis and Human Nutrition |year=2002 |last1=Demmig-Adams |first1=B. |journal=Science |volume=298 |issue=5601 |pmid=12481128 |last2=Adams Ww |first2=3rd}}&lt;/ref&gt; particularly under conditions of high [[irradiance|light intensity]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |pages=337–46 |doi=10.1093/jxb/erh237 |title=Singlet oxygen production in photosynthesis |year=2004 |last1=Krieger-Liszkay |first1=A. |journal=Journal of Experimental Botany |volume=56 |issue=411 |pmid=15310815}}&lt;/ref&gt; This effect is partly offset by the involvement of [[carotenoid]]s in [[photoinhibition]], which involves these antioxidants reacting with over-reduced forms of the [[photosynthetic reaction centre]]s to prevent the production of reactive oxygen species.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |pages=629–34 |doi=10.1038/sj.embor.7400460 |title=Light and oxygenic photosynthesis: Energy dissipation as a protection mechanism against photo-oxidation |year=2005 |last1=Szabó |first1=Ildikó |last2=Bergantino |first2=Elisabetta |last3=Giacometti |first3=Giorgio Mario |journal=EMBO reports |volume=6 |issue=7 |pmid=15995679 |pmc=1369118}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |pages=2–9 |doi=10.1016/j.abb.2004.03.018 |title=Water-soluble carotenoid proteins of cyanobacteria |year=2004 |last1=Kerfeld |first1=C |journal=Archives of Biochemistry and Biophysics |volume=430 |pmid=15325905 |issue=1}}&lt;/ref&gt;

== Metabolites ==
=== Overview ===

Antioxidants are classified into two broad divisions, depending on whether they are soluble in [[water]] ([[hydrophile|hydrophilic]]) or in lipids ([[hydrophobe|hydrophobic]]). In general, water-soluble antioxidants react with oxidants in the cell [[cytosol]] and the [[blood plasma]], while lipid-soluble antioxidants protect [[cell membrane]]s from lipid peroxidation.&lt;ref name=&quot;Sies&quot; /&gt; These compounds may be synthesized in the body or obtained from the diet.&lt;ref name=&quot;Vertuani&quot; /&gt; The different antioxidants are present at a wide range of concentrations in [[Bodily fluid|body fluids]] and tissues, with some such as glutathione or [[ubiquinone]] mostly present within cells, while others such as [[uric acid]] are more evenly distributed (see table below). Some antioxidants are only found in a few organisms and these compounds can be important in [[pathogen]]s and can be [[virulence factor]]s.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |pmid=8993856 |year=1997 |last1=Miller |first1=RA |last2=Britigan |first2=BE |title=Role of oxidants in microbial pathophysiology |volume=10 |issue=1 |pages=1–18 |pmc=172912 |journal=Clinical microbiology reviews}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The relative importance and interactions between these different antioxidants is a very complex question, with the various metabolites and enzyme systems having [[synergy|synergistic]] and interdependent effects on one another.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |pages=949–62 |doi=10.1016/S0278-6915(99)00090-3 |title=Intracellular Antioxidants: From Chemical to Biochemical Mechanisms |year=1999 |last1=Chaudiere |first1=J |journal=Food and Chemical Toxicology |volume=37 |issue=9–10 |pmid=10541450 |last2=Ferrari-Iliou |first2=R}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |pages=213–9 |doi=10.1111/j.1432-1033.1993.tb18025.x |title=Strategies of antioxidant defense |year=1993 |last1=Sies |first1=Helmut |journal=European Journal of Biochemistry |volume=215 |issue=2 |pmid=7688300}}&lt;/ref&gt; The action of one antioxidant may therefore depend on the proper function of other members of the antioxidant system.&lt;ref name=&quot;Vertuani&quot; /&gt; The amount of protection provided by any one antioxidant will also depend on its concentration, its reactivity towards the particular reactive oxygen species being considered, and the status of the antioxidants with which it interacts.&lt;ref name=&quot;Vertuani&quot; /&gt;

Some compounds contribute to antioxidant defense by [[chelation|chelating]] [[transition metal]]s and preventing them from catalyzing the production of free radicals in the cell. Particularly important is the ability to [[sequestering|sequester]] [[iron]], which is the function of [[iron-binding proteins]] such as [[transferrin]] and [[ferritin]].&lt;ref name=&quot;Pathways Ofoxidativedamage&quot;/&gt; [[Selenium]] and [[zinc]] are commonly referred to as ''antioxidant nutrients'', but these [[chemical element]]s have no antioxidant action themselves and are instead required for the activity of some antioxidant enzymes, as is discussed below.

